# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: timsort-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] A sorting algorithm falls into the **adaptive sort** family if it takes advantage of existing order in its input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] It benefits from the presortedness in the input sequence – or a limited amount of disorder for various definitions of measures of disorder – and sorts faster.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Adaptive sorting is usually performed by modifying existing sorting algorithms.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Comparison-based sorting algorithms have traditionally dealt with achieving an optimal bound of *O*(*n* log *n*) when dealing with time complexity.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Adaptive sort takes advantage of the existing order of the input to try to achieve better times, so that the time taken by the algorithm to sort is a smoothly growing function of the size of the sequence *and* the disorder in the sequence.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] In other words, the more presorted the input is, the faster it should be sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] This is an attractive feature for a sorting algorithm because sequences that nearly sorted are common in practice.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Thus, the performance of existing sorting algorithms can be improved by taking into account the existing order in the input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] A classic example of an adaptive sorting algorithm is insertion sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] In this sorting algorithm, the input is scanned from left to right, repeatedly finding the position of the current item, and inserting it into an array of previously sorted items.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] The performance of this algorithm can be described in terms of the number of inversions in the input, and then ⁠ $T(n)$ ⁠ will be roughly equal to ⁠ $I(A)+(n-1)$ ⁠, where ⁠ $I(A)$ ⁠ is the number of inversions.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Using this measure of presortedness – being relative to the number of inversions – insertion sort takes less time to sort the closer the array of data is to being sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Other examples of adaptive sorting algorithms are adaptive heap sort, adaptive merge sort, patience sort, Shellsort, smoothsort, splaysort, Timsort, and Cartesian tree sorting.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] In computer science, **best**, **worst**, and **average cases** of a given algorithm express what the resource usage is *at least*, *at most* and *on average*, respectively.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Usually the resource being considered is running time, i.e. time complexity, but could also be memory or some other resource.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Best case is the function which performs the minimum number of steps on input data of n elements.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst case is the function which performs the maximum number of steps on input data of size n.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Average case is the function which performs an average number of steps on input data of n elements.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] In real-time computing, the worst-case execution time is often of particular concern since it is important to know how much time might be needed *in the worst case* to guarantee that the algorithm will always finish on time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Average performance and worst-case performance are the most used in algorithm analysis.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Less widely found is best-case performance, but it does have uses: for example, where the best cases of individual tasks are known, they can be used to improve the accuracy of an overall worst-case analysis.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Computer scientists use probabilistic analysis techniques, especially expected value, to determine expected running times.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] The terms are used in other contexts; for example the worst- and best-case outcome of an epidemic, worst-case temperature to which an electronic circuit element is exposed, etc.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Where components of specified tolerance are used, devices must be designed to work properly with the worst-case combination of tolerances and external conditions.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] The term *best-case performance* is used in computer science to describe an algorithm's behavior under optimal conditions.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] For example, the best case for a simple linear search on a list occurs when the desired element is the first element of the list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Development and choice of algorithms is rarely based on best-case performance: most academic and commercial enterprises are more interested in improving average-case complexity and worst-case performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Algorithms may also be trivially modified to have good best-case running time by hard-coding solutions to a finite set of inputs, making the measure almost meaningless.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst-case performance analysis and average-case performance analysis have some similarities, but in practice usually require different tools and approaches.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Determining what *typical input* means is difficult, and often that average input has properties which make it difficult to characterise mathematically (consider, for instance, algorithms that are designed to operate on strings of text).
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Similarly, even when a sensible description of a particular "average case" (which will probably only be applicable for some uses of the algorithm) is possible, they tend to result in more difficult analysis of equations.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst-case analysis gives a *safe* analysis (the worst case is never underestimated), but one which can be overly *pessimistic*, since there may be no (realistic) input that would take this many steps.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] In some situations it may be necessary to use a pessimistic analysis in order to guarantee safety.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Often however, a pessimistic analysis may be too pessimistic, so an analysis that gets closer to the real value but may be optimistic (perhaps with some known low probability of failure) can be a much more practical approach.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] One modern approach in academic theory to bridge the gap between worst-case and average-case analysis is called smoothed analysis.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] When analyzing algorithms which often take a small time to complete, but periodically require a much larger time, amortized analysis can be used to determine the worst-case running time over a (possibly infinite) series of operations.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] This **amortized** cost can be much closer to the average cost, while still providing a guaranteed upper limit on the running time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] So e.g. online algorithms are frequently based on amortized analysis.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] The worst-case analysis is related to the worst-case complexity.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Many algorithms with bad worst-case performance have good average-case performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] For problems we want to solve, this is a good thing: we can hope that the particular instances we care about are average.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] For cryptography, this is very bad: we want typical instances of a cryptographic problem to be hard.
[src:timsort-algorithm/best-worst-and-average-case] Here methods like random self-reducibility can be used for some specific problems to show that the worst case is no harder than the average case, or, equivalently, that the average case is no easier than the worst case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When people manually sort cards in a bridge hand, most use a method that is similar to insertion sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Insertion sort iterates, consuming one input element each repetition, and grows a sorted output list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] At each iteration, insertion sort removes one element from the input data, finds the correct location within the sorted list, and inserts it there.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It repeats until no input elements remain.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Sorting is typically done in-place, by iterating up the array, growing the sorted list behind it.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] At each array-position, it checks the value there against the largest value in the sorted list (which happens to be next to it, in the previous array-position checked).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If larger, it leaves the element in place and moves to the next.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If smaller, it finds the correct position within the sorted list, shifts all the larger values up to make a space, and inserts into that correct position.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The resulting array after *k* iterations has the property where the first *k* + 1 entries are sorted ("+1" because the first entry is skipped).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] with each element greater than *x* copied to the right as it is compared against *x*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] To perform an insertion sort, begin at the left-most element of the array and invoke *Insert* to insert each element encountered into its correct position.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The ordered sequence into which the element is inserted is stored at the beginning of the array in the set of indices already examined.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Each insertion overwrites a single value: the value being inserted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The outer loop runs over all the elements except the first one, because the single-element prefix `A[0:1]` is trivially sorted, so the invariant that the first `i` entries are sorted is true from the start.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The inner loop moves element `A[i]` to its correct place so that after the loop, the first `i+1` elements are sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Note that the `**and**`-operator in the test must use short-circuit evaluation, otherwise the test might result in an array bounds error, when `j=0` and it tries to evaluate `A[j-1] > A[j]` (i.e. accessing `A[-1]` fails).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The new inner loop shifts elements to the right to clear a spot for `x = A[i]`.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm can also be implemented in a recursive way.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The initial call would be *`insertionSortR(A, length(A)-1)`*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It does not make the code any shorter, it also does not reduce the execution time, but it increases the additional memory consumption from O(1) to O(N) (at the deepest level of recursion the stack contains N references to the `A` array, each with accompanying value of variable `n` from N down to 1).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The best case input is an array that is already sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In this case insertion sort has a linear running time (i.e., O(*n*)).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] During each iteration, the first remaining element of the input is only compared with the right-most element of the sorted subsection of the array.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The simplest worst case input is an array sorted in reverse order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The set of all worst case inputs consists of all arrays where each element is the smallest or second-smallest of the elements before it.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In these cases every iteration of the inner loop will scan and shift the entire sorted subsection of the array before inserting the next element.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] This gives insertion sort a quadratic running time (i.e., O(*n*2)).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The average case is also quadratic, which makes insertion sort impractical for sorting large arrays.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Example: The following table shows the steps for sorting the sequence {3, 7, 4, 9, 5, 2, 6, 1}.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In each step, the key under consideration is underlined.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The key that was moved (or left in place because it was the biggest yet considered) in the previous step is marked with an asterisk.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Insertion sort is very similar to selection sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] As in selection sort, after *k* passes through the array, the first *k* elements are in sorted order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] However, the fundamental difference between the two algorithms is that insertion sort scans backwards from the current key, while selection sort scans forwards.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] This results in selection sort making the first k elements the *k* smallest elements of the unsorted input, while in insertion sort they are simply the first *k* elements of the input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] On average (assuming the rank of the (*k* + 1)-st element rank is random), insertion sort will require comparing and shifting half of the previous *k* elements, meaning that insertion sort will perform about half as many comparisons as selection sort on average.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In the worst case for insertion sort (when the input array is reverse-sorted), insertion sort performs just as many comparisons as selection sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In general, insertion sort will write to the array O(*n*2) times, whereas selection sort will write only O(n) times.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] For this reason selection sort may be preferable in cases where writing to memory is significantly more expensive than reading, such as with EEPROM or flash memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Therefore, a useful optimization in the implementation of those algorithms is a hybrid approach, using the simpler algorithm when the array has been divided to a small size.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Shell made substantial improvements to the algorithm; the modified version is called Shell sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The sorting algorithm compares elements separated by a distance that decreases on each pass.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Shell sort has distinctly improved running times in practical work, with two simple variants requiring O(*n*3/2) and O(*n*4/3) running time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If the cost of comparisons exceeds the cost of swaps, as is the case for example with string keys stored by reference or with human interaction (such as choosing one of a pair displayed side-by-side), then using *binary insertion sort* may yield better performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Binary insertion sort employs a binary search to determine the correct location to insert new elements, and therefore performs ⌈log2 *n*⌉ comparisons in the worst case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When each element in the array is searched for and inserted this is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm as a whole still has a running time of O(*n*2) on average because of the series of swaps required for each insertion.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The number of swaps can be reduced by calculating the position of multiple elements before moving them.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] For example, if the target position of two elements is calculated before they are moved into the proper position, the number of swaps can be reduced by about 25% for random data.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In the extreme case, this variant works similar to merge sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] A variant named *binary merge sort* uses a *binary insertion sort* to sort groups of 32 elements, followed by a final sort using merge sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It combines the speed of insertion sort on small data sets with the speed of merge sort on large data sets.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] To avoid having to make a series of swaps for each insertion, the input could be stored in a linked list, which allows elements to be spliced into or out of the list in constant time when the position in the list is known.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] However, searching a linked list requires sequentially following the links from each element to the next (or previous) element: a linked list does not have random access, so it cannot use a faster method such as binary search to find the insertion point for an unsorted element.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Therefore, the running time required for searching is O(*n*), and the time for sorting is O(*n*2).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If a more sophisticated data structure (e.g., heap or binary tree) is used, the time required for searching and insertion can be reduced significantly; this is the essence of heap sort and binary tree sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In 2006 Bender, Martin Farach-Colton, and Mosteiro published a new variant of insertion sort called *library sort* or *gapped insertion sort* that leaves a small number of unused spaces (i.e., "gaps") spread throughout the array.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The benefit is that insertions need only shift elements over until a gap is reached.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The authors show that this sorting algorithm runs with high probability in O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If a skip list is used, the insertion time is brought down to O(log *n*), and swaps are not needed because the skip list is implemented on a linked list structure.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The final running time for insertion would be O(*n* log *n*).
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If the items are stored in a linked list, then the list can be sorted with O(1) additional space.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm starts with an initially empty (and therefore trivially sorted) list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The input items are taken off the list one at a time, and then inserted in the proper place in the sorted list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When the input list is empty, the sorted list has the desired result.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm below uses a trailing pointer for the insertion into the sorted list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] A simpler recursive method rebuilds the list each time (rather than splicing) and can use O(*n*) stack space.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Repeatedly merge sublists to produce new sorted sublists until there is only one sublist remaining.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort is efficient because merging and sorting two sublists can be performed in linear time, provided that the sublists are already sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Example C-like code using indices for top-down merge sort algorithm that recursively splits the list into sublists (called *runs* in this example) until sublist size is 1, then merges those sublists to produce a sorted list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The copy back step is avoided with alternating the direction of the merge with each level of recursion (except for an initial one-time copy, that can be avoided too).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] As a simple example, consider an array with two elements.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The elements are copied to `b`, then merged back to `a`.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] If there are four elements, when the bottom of the recursion level is reached, single element runs from `a` are merged to `b`, and then at the next higher level of recursion, those two-element runs are merged to `a`.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This pattern continues with each level of recursion.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Sorting the entire array is accomplished by topDownMergeSort(a, b, a.length).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Pseudocode for top-down merge sort algorithm which recursively divides the input list into smaller sublists until the sublists are trivially sorted, and then merges the sublists while returning up the call chain.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In this example, the merge function merges the left and right sublists.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Pseudocode for bottom-up merge sort algorithm which uses a small fixed size array of references to nodes, where `array[i]` is either a reference to a list of size 2*i* or *nil*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] *node* is a reference or pointer to a node.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The `merge()` function would be similar to the one shown in the top-down merge lists example, it merges two already sorted lists, and handles empty lists.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In this case, `merge()` would use *node* for its input parameters and return value.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Haskell-like pseudocode, showing how merge sort can be implemented in such a language using constructs and ideas from functional programming.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In sorting *n* objects, merge sort has an average and worst-case performance of O(*n* log *n*) comparisons.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The closed form follows from the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The number of comparisons made by merge sort in the worst case is given by the sorting numbers.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] These numbers are equal to or slightly smaller than (*n* ⌈lg *n*⌉ − 2⌈lg *n*⌉ + 1), which is between (*n* lg *n* − *n* + 1) and (*n* lg *n* + *n* + O(lg *n*)).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort's best case takes about half as many iterations as its worst case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the *worst* case, merge sort uses approximately 39% fewer comparisons than quicksort does in its *average* case, and in terms of moves, merge sort's worst case complexity is O(*n* log *n*) - the same complexity as quicksort's best case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort is more efficient than quicksort for some types of lists if the data to be sorted can only be efficiently accessed sequentially, and is thus popular in languages such as Lisp, where sequentially accessed data structures are very common.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Unlike some (efficient) implementations of quicksort, merge sort is a stable sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort's most common implementation does not sort in place; therefore, the memory size of the input must be allocated for the sorted output to be stored in (see below for variations that need only *n*/2 extra spaces).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] A natural merge sort is similar to a bottom-up merge sort except that any naturally occurring runs (sorted sequences) in the input are exploited.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Both monotonic and bitonic (alternating up/down) runs may be exploited, with lists (or equivalently tapes or files) being convenient data structures (used as FIFO queues or LIFO stacks).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the bottom-up merge sort, the starting point assumes each run is one item long.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In practice, random input data will have many short runs that just happen to be sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the typical case, the natural merge sort may not need as many passes because there are fewer runs to merge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the best case, the input is already sorted (i.e., is one run), so the natural merge sort need only make one pass through the data.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In many practical cases, long natural runs are present, and for that reason natural merge sort is exploited as the key component of Timsort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Formally, the natural merge sort is said to be Runs-optimal, where ${\mathtt {Runs}}(L)$ is the number of runs in L , minus one.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Tournament replacement selection sorts are used to gather the initial runs for external sorting algorithms.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Instead of merging two blocks at a time, a ping-pong merge merges four blocks at a time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The four sorted blocks are merged simultaneously to auxiliary space into two sorted blocks, then the two sorted blocks are merged back to main memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Doing so omits the copy operation and reduces the total number of moves by half.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] An early public domain implementation of a four-at-once merge was by WikiSort in 2014, the method was later that year described as an optimization for patience sorting and named a ping-pong merge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Quadsort implemented the method in 2020 and named it a quad merge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] One drawback of merge sort, when implemented on arrays, is its *O*(*n*) working memory requirement.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] An external merge sort is practical to run using disk or tape drives when the data to be sorted is too large to fit into memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] External sorting explains how merge sort is implemented with disk drives.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] A typical tape drive sort uses four tape drives.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] All I/O is sequential (except for rewinds at the end of each pass).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] A minimal implementation can get by with just two record buffers and a few program variables.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Naming the four tape drives as A, B, C, D, with the original data on A, and using only two record buffers, the algorithm is similar to the bottom-up implementation, using pairs of tape drives instead of arrays in memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge two-record sublists from C and D into four-record sublists; writing these alternately to A and B.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Repeat until you have one list containing all the data, sorted—in log2(*n*) passes.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Instead of starting with very short runs, usually a hybrid algorithm is used, where the initial pass will read many records into memory, do an internal sort to create a long run, and then distribute those long runs onto the output set.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, an internal sort of 1024 records will save nine passes.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The internal sort is often large because it has such a benefit.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In fact, there are techniques that can make the initial runs longer than the available internal memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] One of them, the Knuth's 'snowplow' (based on a binary min-heap), generates runs twice as long (on average) as a size of memory used.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] With some overhead, the above algorithm can be modified to use three tapes.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] *O*(*n* log *n*) running time can also be achieved using two queues, or a stack and a queue, or three stacks.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the other direction, using *k* > two tapes (and *O*(*k*) items in memory), we can reduce the number of tape operations in *O*(log *k*) times by using a k/2-way merge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] A more sophisticated merge sort that optimizes tape (and disk) drive usage is the polyphase merge sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] On modern computers, locality of reference can be of paramount importance in software optimization, because multilevel memory hierarchies are used.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Cache-aware versions of the merge sort algorithm, whose operations have been specifically chosen to minimize the movement of pages in and out of a machine's memory cache, have been proposed.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, the **tiled merge sort** algorithm stops partitioning subarrays when subarrays of size S are reached, where S is the number of data items fitting into a CPU's cache.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Each of these subarrays is sorted with an in-place sorting algorithm such as insertion sort, to discourage memory swaps, and normal merge sort is then completed in the standard recursive fashion.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This algorithm has demonstrated better performance on machines that benefit from cache optimization.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort parallelizes well due to the use of the divide-and-conquer method.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Several different parallel variants of the algorithm have been developed over the years.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Some parallel merge sort algorithms are strongly related to the sequential top-down merge algorithm while others have a different general structure and use the K-way merge method.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The sequential merge sort procedure can be described in two phases, the divide phase and the merge phase.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The first consists of many recursive calls that repeatedly perform the same division process until the subsequences are trivially sorted (containing one or no element).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] An intuitive approach is the parallelization of those recursive calls.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This algorithm is the trivial modification of the sequential version and does not parallelize well.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Therefore, its speedup is not very impressive.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] It has a span of $\Theta (n)$ , which is only an improvement of $\Theta (\log n)$ compared to the sequential version (see Introduction to Algorithms).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This is mainly due to the sequential merge method, as it is the bottleneck of the parallel executions.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Better parallelism can be achieved by using a parallel merge algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Cormen et al. present a binary variant that merges two sorted sub-sequences into one sorted output sequence.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In one of the sequences (the longer one if unequal length), the element of the middle index is selected.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Its position in the other sequence is determined in such a way that this sequence would remain sorted if this element were inserted at this position.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus, one knows how many other elements from both sequences are smaller and the position of the selected element in the output sequence can be calculated.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For the partial sequences of the smaller and larger elements created in this way, the merge algorithm is again executed in parallel until the base case of the recursion is reached.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The following pseudocode shows the modified parallel merge sort method using the parallel merge algorithm (adopted from Cormen et al.).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For detailed information about the complexity of the parallel merge procedure, see Merge algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This parallel merge algorithm reaches a parallelism of ${\textstyle \Theta \left({\frac {n}{(\log n)^{2}}}\right)}$ , which is much higher than the parallelism of the previous algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Such a sort can perform well in practice when combined with a fast stable sequential sort, such as insertion sort, and a fast sequential merge as a base case for merging small arrays.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] It seems arbitrary to restrict the merge sort algorithms to a binary merge method, since there are usually p > 2 processors available.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] A better approach may be to use a K-way merge method, a generalization of binary merge, in which k sorted sequences are merged.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This merge variant is well suited to describe a sorting algorithm on a PRAM.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Given an unsorted sequence of n elements, the goal is to sort the sequence with p available processors.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] These elements are distributed equally among all processors and sorted locally using a sequential Sorting algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, the sequence consists of sorted sequences $S_{1},...,S_{p}$ of length ${\textstyle \lceil {\frac {n}{p}}\rceil }$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For simplification let n be a multiple of p , so that ${\textstyle \left\vert S_{i}\right\vert ={\frac {n}{p}}}$ for $i=1,...,p$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] These sequences will be used to perform a multisequence selection/splitter selection.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For $j=1,...,p$ , the algorithm determines splitter elements $v_{j}$ with global rank ${\textstyle k=j{\frac {n}{p}}}$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Then the corresponding positions of $v_{1},...,v_{p}$ in each sequence $S_{i}$ are determined with binary search and thus the $S_{i}$ are further partitioned into p subsequences $S_{i,1},...,S_{i,p}$ with ${\textstyle S_{i,j}:=\{x\in S_{i}|rank(v_{j-1})<rank(x)\leq rank(v_{j})\}}$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Furthermore, the elements of $S_{1,i},...,S_{p,i}$ are assigned to processor i , means all elements between rank ${\textstyle (i-1){\frac {n}{p}}}$ and rank ${\textstyle i{\frac {n}{p}}}$ , which are distributed over all $S_{i}$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus, each processor receives a sequence of sorted sequences.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The fact that the rank k of the splitter elements $v_{i}$ was chosen globally, provides two important properties: On the one hand, k was chosen so that each processor can still operate on ${\textstyle n/p}$ elements after assignment.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The algorithm is perfectly load-balanced.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] On the other hand, all elements on processor i are less than or equal to all elements on processor $i+1$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, each processor performs the *p*-way merge locally and thus obtains a sorted sequence from its sub-sequences.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Because of the second property, no further *p*-way-merge has to be performed, the results only have to be put together in the order of the processor number.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In its simplest form, given p sorted sequences $S_{1},...,S_{p}$ distributed evenly on p processors and a rank k , the task is to find an element x with a global rank k in the union of the sequences.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, this can be used to divide each $S_{i}$ in two parts at a splitter index $l_{i}$ , where the lower part contains only elements which are smaller than x , while the elements bigger than x are located in the upper part.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The presented sequential algorithm returns the indices of the splits in each sequence, e.g. the indices $l_{i}$ in sequences $S_{i}$ such that $S_{i}[l_{i}]$ has a global rank less than k and $\mathrm {rank} \left(S_{i}[l_{i}+1]\right)\geq k$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For the complexity analysis the PRAM model is chosen.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] If the data is evenly distributed over all p , the p-fold execution of the *binarySearch* method has a running time of ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\log \left(n/p\right)\right)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The expected recursion depth is ${\mathcal {O}}\left(\log \left(\textstyle \sum _{i}|S_{i}|\right)\right)={\mathcal {O}}(\log(n))$ as in the ordinary Quickselect.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus the overall expected running time is ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Applied on the parallel multiway merge sort, this algorithm has to be invoked in parallel such that all splitter elements of rank ${\textstyle i{\frac {n}{p}}}$ for $i=1,..,p$ are found simultaneously.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] These splitter elements can then be used to partition each sequence in p parts, with the same total running time of ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\,\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Below, the complete pseudocode of the parallel multiway merge sort algorithm is given.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] We assume that there is a barrier synchronization before and after the multisequence selection such that every processor can determine the splitting elements and the sequence partition properly.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Firstly, each processor sorts the assigned $n/p$ elements locally using a sorting algorithm with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}\left(n/p\;\log(n/p)\right)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] After that, the splitter elements have to be calculated in time ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\,\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Finally, each group of p splits have to be merged in parallel by each processor with a running time of ${\mathcal {O}}(\log(p)\;n/p)$ using a sequential p-way merge algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The multiway merge sort algorithm is very scalable through its high parallelization capability, which allows the use of many processors.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This makes the algorithm a viable candidate for sorting large amounts of data, such as those processed in computer clusters.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Also, since in such systems memory is usually not a limiting resource, the disadvantage of space complexity of merge sort is negligible.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] However, other factors become important in such systems, which are not taken into account when modelling on a PRAM.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Here, the following aspects need to be considered: Memory hierarchy, when the data does not fit into the processors cache, or the communication overhead of exchanging data between processors, which could become a bottleneck when the data can no longer be accessed via the shared memory.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Sanders et al. have presented in their paper a bulk synchronous parallel algorithm for multilevel multiway mergesort, which divides p processors into r groups of size $p'$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Unlike single level multiway mergesort, these sequences are then partitioned into r parts and assigned to the appropriate processor groups.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] These steps are repeated recursively in those groups.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] This reduces communication and especially avoids problems with many small messages.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The hierarchical structure of the underlying real network can be used to define the processor groups (e.g. racks, clusters,...).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort was one of the first sorting algorithms where optimal speed up was achieved, with Richard Cole using a clever subsampling algorithm to ensure *O*(1) merge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Other sophisticated parallel sorting algorithms can achieve the same or better time bounds with a lower constant.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, in 1991 David Powers described a parallelized quicksort (and a related radix sort) that can operate in *O*(log *n*) time on a CRCW parallel random-access machine (PRAM) with *n* processors by performing partitioning implicitly.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Although heapsort has the same time bounds as merge sort, it requires only Θ(1) auxiliary space instead of merge sort's Θ(*n*).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] On typical modern architectures, efficient quicksort implementations generally outperform merge sort for sorting RAM-based arrays.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Quicksorts are preferred when the data size to be sorted is lesser, since the space complexity for quicksort is O(log *n*), it helps in utilizing cache locality better than merge sort (with space complexity O(n)).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] On the other hand, merge sort is a stable sort and is more efficient at handling slow-to-access sequential media.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] As of Perl 5.8, merge sort is its default sorting algorithm (it was quicksort in previous versions of Perl).
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] In Java, the Arrays.sort() methods use merge sort or a tuned quicksort depending on the datatypes and for implementation efficiency switch to insertion sort when fewer than seven array elements are being sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] The Linux kernel uses merge sort for its linked lists.
[src:timsort-algorithm/merge-sort] Timsort, a tuned hybrid of merge sort and insertion sort is used in variety of software platforms and languages including the Java and Android platforms and is used by Python since version 2.3; since version 3.11, Timsort's merge policy was updated to Powersort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In computer science, a **sorting algorithm** is an algorithm that puts elements of a list into an order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most frequently used orders are numerical order and lexicographical order, and either ascending order or descending order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Efficient sorting is important for optimizing the efficiency of other algorithms (such as search and merge algorithms) that require input data to be in sorted lists.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting is also often useful for canonicalizing data and for producing human-readable output.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The output is a permutation (a reordering, yet retaining all of the original elements) of the input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Although some algorithms are designed for sequential access, the highest-performing algorithms assume data is stored in a data structure which allows random access.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] From the beginning of computing, the sorting problem has attracted a great deal of research, perhaps due to the complexity of solving it efficiently despite its simple, familiar statement.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Among the authors of early sorting algorithms around 1951 was Betty Holberton, who worked on ENIAC and UNIVAC.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort was analyzed as early as 1956.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Asymptotically optimal algorithms have been known since the mid-20th century – new algorithms are still being invented, with the widely used Timsort dating to 2002, and the library sort being first published in 2006.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Comparison sorting algorithms have a fundamental requirement of $n\log {n}-1.4427n+O(\log {n})$ comparisons.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Algorithms not based on comparisons, such as counting sort, can have better performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting small arrays optimally (in the fewest comparisons and swaps) or fast (i.e. taking into account machine-specific details) is still an open research problem, with solutions only known for very small arrays (fewer than 20 elements).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Similarly optimal (by various definitions) sorting on a parallel machine is an open research topic.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Stability is important to preserve order over multiple sorts on the same data set.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, say that student records consisting of name and class section are sorted dynamically, first by name, then by class section.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] If a stable sorting algorithm is used in both cases, the sort-by-class-section operation will not change the name order; with an unstable sort, it could be that sorting by section shuffles the name order, resulting in a nonalphabetical list of students.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] More formally, the data being sorted can be represented as a record or tuple of values, and the part of the data that is used for sorting is called the *key*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In the card example, cards are represented as a record (rank, suit), and the key is the rank.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] A sorting algorithm is stable if whenever there are two records R and S with the same key, and R appears before S in the original list, then R will always appear before S in the sorted list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] When equal elements are indistinguishable, such as with integers, or more generally, any data where the entire element is the key, stability is not an issue.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Stability is also not an issue if all keys are different.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Unstable sorting algorithms can be specially implemented to be stable.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] One way of doing this is to artificially extend the key comparison so that comparisons between two objects with otherwise equal keys are decided using the order of the entries in the original input list as a tie-breaker.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Remembering this order, however, may require additional time and space.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] One application for stable sorting algorithms is sorting a list using a primary and secondary key.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, suppose we wish to sort a hand of cards such that the suits are in the order clubs (♣), diamonds (♦), hearts (♥), spades (♠), and within each suit, the cards are sorted by rank.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Within each suit, the stable sort preserves the ordering by rank that was already done.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This idea can be extended to any number of keys and is utilised by radix sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The same effect can be achieved with an unstable sort by using a lexicographic key comparison, which, e.g., compares first by suit, and then compares by rank if the suits are the same.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This analysis assumes that the length of each key is constant and that all comparisons, swaps and other operations can proceed in constant time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Mathematical analysis demonstrates a comparison sort cannot perform better than *O*(*n* log *n*) on average.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Performs a combination of Quicksort, Heapsort, and Insertion sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] in-place stable merge algorithm, such as rotate merge or symmerge.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] An optimization of Selection Sort, which uses a tournament tree to select the min/max.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] comparisons when the data is already sorted or reverse sorted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] An adaptive branchless stable introsort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] An in-place, but unstable variant of Fluxsort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Complexity is influenced by the gap sequence used.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Tight bounds for the average and worst case remain open problems.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Can be run on parallel processors easily.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Noted for its simplicity and small number of element moves.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In-place with theoretically optimal number of writes.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The following table describes integer sorting algorithms and other sorting algorithms that are not comparison sorts.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] These algorithms are not limited to *Ω*(*n* log *n*) unless meet unit-cost random-access machine model as described below.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Samplesort can be used to parallelize any of the non-comparison sorts, by efficiently distributing data into several buckets and then passing down sorting to several processors, with no need to merge as buckets are already sorted between each other.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Some algorithms are slow compared to those discussed above, such as the bogosort with unbounded run time and the stooge sort which has *O*(*n*2.7) run time.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] These sorts are usually described for educational purposes to demonstrate how the run time of algorithms is estimated.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The following table describes some sorting algorithms that are impractical for real-life use in traditional software contexts due to extremely poor performance or specialized hardware requirements.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] While there are a large number of sorting algorithms, in practical implementations a few algorithms predominate.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Insertion sort is widely used for small data sets, while for large data sets an asymptotically efficient sort is used, primarily heapsort, merge sort, or quicksort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Efficient implementations generally use a hybrid algorithm, combining an asymptotically efficient algorithm for the overall sort with insertion sort for small lists at the bottom of a recursion.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Highly tuned implementations use more sophisticated variants, such as Timsort (merge sort, insertion sort, and additional logic), used in Android, Java, and Python, and introsort (quicksort and heapsort), used (in variant forms) in some C++ sort implementations and in .NET.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For more restricted data, such as numbers in a fixed interval, distribution sorts such as counting sort or radix sort are widely used.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort and variants are rarely used in practice, but are commonly found in teaching and theoretical discussions.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] When physically sorting objects (such as alphabetizing papers, tests or books) people intuitively generally use insertion sorts for small sets.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For larger sets, people often first bucket, such as by initial letter, and multiple bucketing allows practical sorting of very large sets.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Often space is relatively cheap, such as by spreading objects out on the floor or over a large area, but operations are expensive, particularly moving an object a large distance – locality of reference is important.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sorts are also practical for physical objects, particularly as two hands can be used, one for each list to merge, while other algorithms, such as heapsort or quicksort, are poorly suited for human use.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Other algorithms, such as library sort, a variant of insertion sort that leaves spaces, are also practical for physical use.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Two of the simplest sorts are insertion sort and selection sort, both of which are efficient on small data, due to low overhead, but not efficient on large data.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Insertion sort is generally faster than selection sort in practice, due to fewer comparisons and good performance on almost-sorted data, and thus is preferred in practice, but selection sort uses fewer writes, and thus is used when write performance is a limiting factor.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The algorithm finds the minimum value, swaps it with the value in the first position, and repeats these steps for the remainder of the list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] It does no more than *n* swaps and thus is useful where swapping is very expensive.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Practical general sorting algorithms are almost always based on an algorithm with average time complexity (and generally worst-case complexity) O(*n* log *n*), of which the most common are heapsort, merge sort, and quicksort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each has advantages and drawbacks, with the most significant being that simple implementation of merge sort uses O(*n*) additional space, and simple implementation of quicksort has O(*n*2) worst-case complexity.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] These problems can be solved or ameliorated at the cost of a more complex algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] While these algorithms are asymptotically efficient on random data, for practical efficiency on real-world data various modifications are used.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] First, the overhead of these algorithms becomes significant on smaller data, so often a hybrid algorithm is used, commonly switching to insertion sort once the data is small enough.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Second, the algorithms often perform poorly on already sorted data or almost sorted data – these are common in real-world data and can be sorted in O(*n*) time by appropriate algorithms.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Finally, they may also be unstable, and stability is often a desirable property in a sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Thus more sophisticated algorithms are often employed, such as Timsort (based on merge sort) or introsort (based on quicksort, falling back to heapsort).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sort has seen a relatively recent surge in popularity for practical implementations, due to its use in the sophisticated algorithm Timsort, which is used for the standard sort routine in the programming languages Python and Java (as of JDK7).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sort itself is the standard routine in Perl, among others, and has been used in Java at least since 2000 in JDK1.3.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The important caveat about quicksort is that its worst-case performance is O(*n*2); while this is rare, in naive implementations (choosing the first or last element as pivot) this occurs for sorted data, which is a common case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most complex issue in quicksort is thus choosing a good pivot element, as consistently poor choices of pivots can result in drastically slower O(*n*2) performance, but good choice of pivots yields O(*n* log *n*) performance, which is asymptotically optimal.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, if at each step the median is chosen as the pivot then the algorithm works in O(*n* log *n*).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Finding the median, such as by the median of medians selection algorithm is however an O(*n*) operation on unsorted lists and therefore exacts significant overhead with sorting.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In practice choosing a random pivot almost certainly yields O(*n* log *n*) performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] If a guarantee of O(*n* log *n*) performance is important, there is a simple modification to achieve that.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The idea, due to Musser, is to set a limit on the maximum depth of recursion.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] If that limit is exceeded, then sorting is continued using the heapsort algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Musser proposed that the limit should be $1+2\lfloor \log _{2}(n)\rfloor$ , which is approximately twice the maximum recursion depth one would expect on average with a randomly ordered array.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The worst-case time complexity of Shellsort is an open problem and depends on the gap sequence used, with known complexities ranging from *O*(*n*2) to *O*(*n*4/3) and Θ(*n* log2 *n*).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This, combined with the fact that Shellsort is in-place, only needs a relatively small amount of code, and does not require use of the call stack, makes it is useful in situations where memory is at a premium, such as in embedded systems and operating system kernels.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort, and variants such as the Comb sort and cocktail sort, are simple, highly inefficient sorting algorithms.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] They are frequently seen in introductory texts due to ease of analysis, but they are rarely used in practice.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Counting sort is applicable when each input is known to belong to a particular set, *S*, of possibilities.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The algorithm runs in O(|*S*| + *n*) time and O(|*S*|) memory where *n* is the length of the input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] It works by creating an integer array of size |*S*| and using the *i*th bin to count the occurrences of the *i*th member of *S* in the input.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each input is then counted by incrementing the value of its corresponding bin.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Afterward, the counting array is looped through to arrange all of the inputs in order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This sorting algorithm often cannot be used because *S* needs to be reasonably small for the algorithm to be efficient, but it is extremely fast and demonstrates great asymptotic behavior as *n* increases.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] It also can be modified to provide stable behavior.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bucket sort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm that generalizes counting sort by partitioning an array into a finite number of buckets.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each bucket is then sorted individually, either using a different sorting algorithm or by recursively applying the bucket sorting algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] A bucket sort works best when the elements of the data set are evenly distributed across all buckets.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In *Algorithms and Data Structures* Niklaus Wirth gives a comparison of the running time of several of the popular algorithms on the Lilith computer.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In this scenario, the total number of comparisons becomes (relatively) less important, and the number of times sections of memory must be copied or swapped to and from the disk can dominate the performance characteristics of an algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Thus, the number of passes and the localization of comparisons can be more important than the raw number of comparisons, since comparisons of nearby elements to one another happen at system bus speed (or, with caching, even at CPU speed), which, compared to disk speed, is virtually instantaneous.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In that scenario, another algorithm may be preferable even if it requires more total comparisons.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] One way to work around this problem, which works well when complex records (such as in a relational database) are being sorted by a relatively small key field, is to create an index into the array and then sort the index, rather than the entire array.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This procedure is sometimes called "tag sort".
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Another technique for overcoming the memory-size problem is using external sorting, for example, one of the ways is to combine two algorithms in a way that takes advantage of the strength of each to improve overall performance.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For instance, the array might be subdivided into chunks of a size that will fit in RAM, the contents of each chunk sorted using an efficient algorithm (such as quicksort), and the results merged using a *k*-way merge similar to that used in merge sort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This is faster than performing either merge sort or quicksort over the entire list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] For sorting very large sets of data that vastly exceed system memory, even the index may need to be sorted using an algorithm or combination of algorithms designed to perform reasonably with virtual memory, i.e., to reduce the amount of swapping required.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Related problems include approximate sorting (sorting a sequence to within a certain amount of the correct order), partial sorting (sorting only the *k* smallest elements of a list, or finding the *k* smallest elements, but unordered) and selection (computing the *k*th smallest element).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] These can be solved inefficiently by a total sort, but more efficient algorithms exist, often derived by generalizing a sorting algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most notable example is quickselect, which is related to quicksort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Conversely, some sorting algorithms can be derived by repeated application of a selection algorithm; quicksort and quickselect can be seen as the same pivoting move, differing only in whether one recurses on both sides (quicksort, divide-and-conquer) or one side (quickselect, decrease-and-conquer).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] A kind of opposite of a sorting algorithm is a shuffling algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] These are fundamentally different because they require a source of random numbers.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Shuffling can also be implemented by a sorting algorithm, namely by a random sort: assigning a random number to each element of the list and then sorting based on the random numbers.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This is generally not done in practice, however, and there is a well-known simple and efficient algorithm for shuffling: the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting algorithms are ineffective for finding an order in many situations.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] Usually, when elements have no reliable comparison function (crowdsourced preferences like voting systems), comparisons are very costly (sports), or when it would be impossible to pairwise compare all elements for all criteria (search engines).
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] In these cases, the problem is usually referred to as *ranking* and the goal is to find the "best" result for some criteria according to probabilities inferred from comparisons or rankings.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] A common example is in chess, where players are ranked with the Elo rating system, and rankings are determined by a tournament system instead of a sorting algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] There are sorting algorithms for a "noisy" (potentially incorrect) comparator and sorting algorithms for a pair of "fast and dirty" (i.e.
[src:timsort-algorithm/stable-sort] This can be useful when the full comparison function is costly.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The galloping technique derives from Carlsson, Levcopoulos, and O.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Petersson's 1990 paper "Sublinear merging and natural merge sort" and Peter McIlroy's 1993 paper "Optimistic Sorting and Information Theoretic Complexity".
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Timsort was designed to take advantage of *runs* of consecutive ordered elements that already exist in most real-world data, *natural runs*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] It iterates over the data collecting elements into runs and simultaneously putting those runs in a stack.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Whenever the runs on the top of the stack match a merge criterion, they are merged.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] This goes on until all data is traversed; then, all runs are merged two at a time and only one sorted run remains.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The advantage of merging ordered runs instead of merging fixed size sub-lists (as done by traditional mergesort) is that it decreases the total number of comparisons needed to sort the entire list.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Each run has a minimum size, which is based on the size of the input and is defined at the start of the algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] If a run is smaller than this minimum run size, insertion sort is used to add more elements to the run until the minimum run size is reached.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Timsort is a stable sorting algorithm (order of elements with same key is kept) and strives to perform balanced merges (a merge thus merges runs of similar sizes).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In order to achieve sorting stability, only consecutive runs are merged.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Between two non-consecutive runs, there can be an element with the same key inside the runs.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Merging those two runs would change the order of equal keys.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] If any of these invariants is violated, *Y* is merged with the smaller of *X* or *Z* and the invariants are checked again.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Once the invariants hold, the search for a new run in the data can start.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] These invariants maintain merges as being approximately balanced while maintaining a compromise between delaying merging for balance, exploiting fresh occurrence of runs in cache memory and making merge decisions relatively simple.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The original merge sort implementation is not in-place and it has a space overhead of N (data size).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In-place merge sort implementations exist, but have a high time overhead.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In order to achieve a middle term, Timsort performs a merge sort with a small time overhead and smaller space overhead than N.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] First, Timsort performs a binary search to find the location where the first element of the second run would be inserted in the first ordered run, keeping it ordered.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Then, it performs the same algorithm to find the location where the last element of the first run would be inserted in the second ordered run, keeping it ordered.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Elements before and after these locations are already in their correct place and do not need to be merged.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Then, the smaller of these shrunk runs is copied into temporary memory, and the copied elements are merged with the larger shrunk run into the now free space.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] If the leftmost shrunk run is smaller, the merge proceeds from left to right.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] If the rightmost shrunk run is smaller, merging proceeds from right to left (i.e. beginning with elements at the ends of the temporary space and leftmost run, and filling the free space from its end).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] This optimization reduces the number of required element movements, the running time and the temporary space overhead in the general case.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Note that both runs are already sorted individually.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The smallest element of the second run is 4 and it would have to be added at the fourth position of the first run in order to preserve its order (assuming that the first position of a run is 1).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The largest element of the first run is 10 and it would have to be added at the fifth position of the second run in order to preserve its order.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Therefore, [1, 2, 3] and [12, 14, 17] are already in their final positions and the runs in which elements movements are required are [6, 10] and [4, 5, 7, 9].
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] With this knowledge, we only need to allocate a temporary buffer of size 2 instead of 4.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Merging can be done in both directions: left-to-right, as in the traditional mergesort, or right-to-left.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] An individual merge of runs R1 and R2 keeps the count of consecutive elements selected from a run.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] When this number reaches the *minimum galloping threshold* (*min_gallop*), Timsort considers that it is likely that many consecutive elements may still be selected from that run and switches into galloping mode.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Let us assume that R1 is responsible for triggering it.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In this mode, the algorithm performs a two-stage search for the place in the run R1 where the next element *x* of the run R2 would be inserted.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In the first stage it performs an exponential search, also known as a galloping search, until finding a *k* such that R1[2*k−1* − 1] < x <= R1[2*k* − 1], i.e. a region of uncertainty comprising 2*k−1* − 1 consecutive elements of R1.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The second stage performs a straight binary search of this region to find the exact location in R1 for *x*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Galloping mode is an attempt to adapt the merge algorithm to the pattern of intervals between elements in runs.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In some cases galloping mode requires more comparisons than a simple linear search.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] According to benchmarks done by the developer, galloping is beneficial only when the initial element of one run is not one of the first seven elements of the other run.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] To avoid the drawbacks of galloping mode, two actions are taken: (1) When galloping is found to be less efficient than binary search, galloping mode is exited.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] (2) The success or failure of galloping is used to adjust *min_gallop*.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] If the selected element is from the same array that returned an element previously, *min_gallop* is reduced by one, thus encouraging the return to galloping mode.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Otherwise, the value is incremented by one, thus discouraging a return to galloping mode.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In the case of random data, the value of *min_gallop* becomes so large that galloping mode never recurs.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In order to also take advantage of data sorted in descending order, Timsort reverses strictly descending runs when it finds them and adds them to the stack of runs.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Since descending runs are later blindly reversed, excluding runs with equal elements maintains the algorithm's stability; i.e., equal elements won't be reversed.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Because merging is most efficient when the number of runs is equal to, or slightly less than, a power of two, and notably less efficient when the number of runs is slightly more than a power of two, Timsort chooses *minrun* to try to ensure the former condition.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] As described above, Timsort consists of several pieces, too long to describe here in pseudocode.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In the worst case, Timsort takes $O(n\log n)$ comparisons to sort an array of n elements.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In the best case, which occurs when the input is already sorted, it runs in linear time, meaning that it is an adaptive sorting algorithm.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] For an input that has r runs of sorted elements, the running time is $O(n\log r)$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The formula for the running time is given as $n+n\mathrm {H}$ rather than more simply $n\mathrm {H}$ , to account for the possibility that the entropy can be less than one.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The above behavior regarding the run-length entropy $\mathrm {H}$ is purely derived by Timsort's merge criteria, as that is the part responsible for detecting already-sorted parts.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The "galloping" routine exploits a new property that can be described as the dual-run entropy $\mathrm {H} ^{*}$ : $\mathrm {H} ^{*}=-\sum _{i=1}^{s}{\frac {n_{i}}{n}}\log _{2}{\frac {n_{i}}{n}}.$ where s the number of times "galloping" is interrupted by and $s\leq r$ .
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] It can be proven that TimSort takes up to $O(n+n\mathrm {H} )$ element moves and $O(n+n\mathrm {H} ^{*})$ value comparisons.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Timsort has inspired many similar algorithms, both in when they decide to merge (the nature of merge trees) and how they perform a merge (especially the galloping heuristic).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In 2015, Dutch and German researchers in the EU FP7 ENVISAGE project found a bug in the standard implementation of Timsort.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] It was fixed in 2015 in Python, Java, and Android.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] Specifically, the invariants on stacked run sizes ensure a tight upper bound on the maximum size of the required stack.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The implementation preallocated a stack sufficient to sort 264 bytes of input, and avoided further overflow checks.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] However, the guarantee requires the invariants to apply to *every* group of three consecutive runs, but the implementation only checked it for the top three.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] As a consequence, for certain inputs the allocated size is not sufficient to hold all unmerged runs.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] In Java, this generates for those inputs an array-out-of-bound exception.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The smallest input that triggers this exception in Java and Android v7 is of size 67108864 (226).
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The Java implementation was corrected by increasing the size of the preallocated stack based on an updated worst-case analysis.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] The article also showed by formal methods how to establish the intended invariant by checking that the *four* topmost runs in the stack satisfy the two rules above.
[src:timsort-algorithm/timsort] This approach was initially adopted by Python until it switched to Powersort in 2022 with the release of Python 3.11.
